weapons to get the job done.=A0A powerful warrior,=A0who knows=A0very wel=\r\nl how=A0powerful he=A0himself is, not letting that sense of power pervert h=\r\nis mind even for a moment is an amazing phenomenon. This kind of self-contr=\r\nol is rare and worthy of comtemplation, specially by anyone who feels, ever=\r\n so slightly, that he/she has some form of power or influence in\n this worl=\r\nd in any sphere.=A0Rama had no malice for anyone. Not even Ravana, by the e=\r\nnd of the war at least. He was the very personification of Satwa. In Satwa,=\r\n conflict and malice and cunningness are impossible.\n&gt;=A0\n&gt;Recently, a frie=\r\nnd of mine told me that he has learnt all his life that one must listen to =\r\nKrshna&#39;s advice, but only follow what Rama did, and not what Krshna did. I =\r\ndisagree with this vehemently. If one reads entire Krshna&#39;s life=A0with an =\r\nobjective mind, Krshna of Vrndavana, Krshna of Mathura, Krshna of Kurushetr=\r\na, Krshna the Jagat Guru who speaks the Gita, one will find that what Krshn=\r\na the Guru adviced in the Gita,=A0Krshna the=A0Divine Worker=A0himself foll=\r\nowed it all through his life at every instance. It is his=A0perfect detachm=\r\nent under all circumstances of life, from childhood=A0to his death,=A0that =\r\nmakes me wonder, was this a man or was this a God? Can a man even do someth=\r\ning like this? It is as if there is a part of Krshna who is always separate=\r\n from everything, and silently watches the whole scene with a bemused smile=\r\n. He had not a single personal stake in the Mahabharata. Rama at least had =\r\nhis wife abducted for him to start a war against Ravana.\n But Krshna had ze=\r\nro=A0personal stake in the Mahabharata.=A0After liberating his parents from=\r\n Kamsa, very soon he went off to meet the Pandavas. From out of nowhere he =\r\nforced himself into the politics of the Mahabharata, and precipitated a gre=\r\nat war to cleanse the world of burden. While Lakshmana devoutly followed Ra=\r\nma all along the Ramayana and they were like an inseparable pair, as=A0Bala=\r\nrama in his next incarnation=A0he could=A0hardly understand Krshna. There a=\r\nre so many occassions where Balarama asks Krshna, what are they doing with =\r\nall these kings, and=A0that they should=A0return to their village in Vrndav=\r\nana. Krshna merely smiles. He knows that not everyone will understand every=\r\nthing. But that cannot stop him from following his dharma, with perfect det=\r\nachement from eveyrthing of this plane. Neither false praises, nor wrong ac=\r\ncusations by his close people can affect him one bit. And I am not even cou=\r\nnting the miracles he perfromed as a Divine Child. So I\n worship Krshna, be=\r\ncause I have not yet met or heard of read of=A0a single sadhaka or saint or=\r\n ordinary man or mahatma=A0who has displayed this kind of perfected detachm=\r\nent through thick and thin, yet not withdrawing from the world or actively =\r\nperforming a larger dharma.\n&gt;=A0\n&gt;I started appreciating Swami Vivekanada m=\r\nore after I understood a bit of the Krshna Avatara. That was the last known=\r\n saint who lived a whirlwind life in the middle of a circus-stoplight of fa=\r\nme and accusations, on one side adoring admirers and on the other bitter en=\r\nemies accusing him of=A0being a heretic=A0right upto the=A0very end of his =\r\nbrief life,=A0and yet none of that affected him to any great degree. He fac=\r\ned terrific racism in the America, yet not a single speech of his reflects =\r\nthe slightest trace of bitterness, anger, or negativity. That is such a fan=\r\ntastic achievement, IMHO.\n&gt;=A0\n&gt;I agree with you, Narasimha, for most of us=\r\n it is better to=A0try to=A0mould ones life=A0with the same kind of supreme=\r\n selflessness that Rama showed all along.=A0Not just worship Rama=A0but mor=\r\ne importantly study=A0his life and imbibe,=A0to whatever degree possible, t=\r\nhe quality he represented.=A0Maybe, just maybe,