 main avatars with the evolution o=\r\nf life on earth. From the aquatic, to the amphibian, to the land-animal, to=\r\n the half-animal-half-man, to the dwarf man (first human life form who imme=\r\ndiately takes possession of this earth represented by Vamana&#39;s 3 steps), to=\r\n the Rajashik avatara of Parashurama moving around with an axe, to the Satt=\r\nwa Guna Avatara of Rama, to the Nirguna Avatara of Krshna. Also, this indic=\r\nates that spirituality is not to be separated into another world, but is a =\r\nprogressive realization of the various manifestation and potentials that li=\r\ne inherent in the consciousness and its development through various life-fo=\r\nrms. Larger spirituality of earth and evolution go hand in hand. That is Na=\r\nture&#39;s grand design for life on earth.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;4. In this specifc contex=\r\nt, I am only focusing on the parable of these main 9/10 Avatars. It is not =\r\nmy contention that if one worships say Matysa Avatara, one will not attain =\r\nto a state of liberation of the soul. As is the nature of spiritual cosmolo=\r\ngy in Hinduism, any Devata can lead a person to any depth of realization. A=\r\nnd each one of the Avatars of Vishnu are self-realized in their own way and=\r\n can be consider super-massive spiritual dynamos.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;=A05. Of t=\r\nhese, naturally, Rama and Krshna are most adored because they represent a s=\r\ntage of evolution, both inside as well as outside, which society can relate=\r\n of much easier, in this age. Rama represents, for me, the stage of most sa=\r\ntwic mind. A satwic mind is in control of itself. It known how to transform=\r\n the animal tendencies within and without - monkeys - into a constructive f=\r\norce for a greater purpose. However, as with a state of full Sattwa Guna, t=\r\nhere can be instances, even though few, of dejection. For it is static in n=\r\nature and will change only when circumstances force it to. As per the Valmi=\r\nki Ramayana, Rama did feel dejected while searching for Sita in the forest.=\r\n He did have a moments fear before the final assault on Ravana, which was d=\r\nispelled by Agsatha when the later revealed the stotra of the Sun to Rama. =\r\nAt the end of the final battle, Rama tells Sita, in a most dispassionate ma=\r\nnner, that he killed Ravana not to rescue her, but it\n was the Dharma to do=\r\n so, and to unhold his family honour. That too was the dharma of that age w=\r\nhen he lived, family honor. The way I look at this grand epic, and I bow hu=\r\nmbly to the genius of Rishis Valmiki for representing the things as they ar=\r\ne, as a scribe, as a poet, as an observer, and not adding his own preferenc=\r\nes to it anywhere, in the 14 years of tribulation that Rama faced which cul=\r\nminated into his killing Ravana, he changed into the most dispassionate lea=\r\nder, such that no personal consideration or emotions or passions can overtu=\r\nrn the Rajadharma. His life is a lesson of what a true leader must be! Krsh=\r\nna, OTOH, had this immaculate detachment right from birth. I am not taking =\r\nhis=A0 supernatural feats into account. It is his singular and constant det=\r\nachment from situations, from people, from environment, from circumstances =\r\nthat mark his life. At the age of eight, he decides to leave Vrindavana for=\r\n Mathura. All his friends, his foster parents,\n his village-folks who so lo=\r\nved him, pleaded with him that it would make no sense for him to leave the =\r\nshelter, love and comfort of his happy, settled village life and head into =\r\nan unknown destiny and destination. Krshna tried to reason with them, then =\r\nhe understood that they won&#39;t understand, he promised he will return back o=\r\nnce his work in Mathura is over. He never returned. Later, much later, when=\r\n the Gopis came to him asking him to participate in their dance, he obliged=\r\n. But the moment some of them started getting jealous and possessive of Krs=\r\nhna, he removed himself quietly from the scene, saying that he belongs to e=\r\nveryone equally and no one has any special right over him. When Shishupala =\r\nabused Krshna, the later merely kept dropping flowers on the floor, smiling=\r\n and counting. The moment the 100th abuse was over, he swiftly cut off Shis=\r\nhupala&#39;s head and was back into his poise. But when Bhurishrava unfairly ac=\r\ncused Krshna of being a revolutionist\n and charlatan, Krshna did not kill h=\r\nim. When Duryodhana, who used to think of Krshna as another black magician,=\r\n wanted to arrest him, Krshna showed his vikarala roopa in the assembly of =\r\nkings, yet he did not finish the enemies off. The very next moment he was b=\r\nack into his own poised self. Never in the whole Mahabharata is there one i=\r\nnstance of his going overboard, never a single shade of depression, equivoc=\r\nation, or lack of confidence in his actions, irrespective of what others sa=\r\ny or think of him. And then right in the middle of the greatest war he had =\r\nthe perfect equipoise to deliver the most sublime spiritual philosophy. Tha=\r\nt is why his life remains the best ideal of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karma-Yo=\r\ngi by definition can never be dejected. It is impossible. Neither the actio=\r\nn nor the results belong to the instrument. When running away from the batt=\r\nle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or when advising Bheema to tear apart J=\r\narashanda, or gesturing Bheema\n to hit Duryodhana below the waist, or getti=\r\nng Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some Divine Intuition, knew e=\r\nxactly how the situations must be lined up which would cause the destructio=\r\nn of these people. This kind of knowledge cannot come by the rational think=\r\ning. But happens when one is constantly and consciously connected to the Un=\r\niversal Force. We do not find these kind of complex situations in the Rama =\r\nAvatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana. Of course, if we take the Adhbut=\r\n Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts and retelling, we get a different =\r\npicture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have a 1000 headed demon attacking Rama=\r\n after he kills Ravana, and then Sita turns into Adya Shakti and demolishes=\r\n the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships her. But if we take only the Ramay=\r\nana and the Mahabharata, the picture that emerges is very clear. Rama is th=\r\ne embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore he displays all the great character=\r\nistics of satwa, chief\n of which is self-control, as well as the occasional=\r\n sadness caused due to separation from his wife Sita whom, at least until R=\r\navana was destroyed, he loved very dearly. Satwa guna creates a true saint,=\r\n but can also cause some grief when the stability is shaken. Krshna was gun=\r\natita. He had no attachment to anything in this world - man, women, deva, d=\r\nanava, friend, enemy - and therefore he was never affected any trace of neg=\r\native emotion. His Ananda never left him even in the most trying situations=\r\n. 6. Buddha was great spiritual force in this world. But I do not see him f=\r\nit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars. His realization, the one he advoc=\r\nated, is a static realization, an end in a void. This is clearly denying of=\r\n the reality of this earth. I find this not in tune with what either Rama o=\r\nr Krshna espoused. None of them negated this world. If negation of this wor=\r\nld and life is the final aim, then why send so many avatars at crucial stag=\r\nes of\n evolutionary development? If the spiritual impact on masses is the r=\r\neason for Buddha being an Avatara, then why not Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They=\r\n are no less impactful in that sense. But do they fit in the scheme of spir=\r\nitual line that these 9 Avataras of Narayana indicate in a most logical man=\r\nner? No. As such many vaishnava traditions in parts of India, do not consid=\r\ner Buddha to be an avatara. Realization, to be complete and holistic, must =\r\nbe both static and dynamic, outside of life as well as inside of life. That=\r\n is why the Tantras formed their own kind of spiritual philosophy, of the w=\r\norld as body of Shakti and therefore an object of reverence and realization=\r\n. 7. The original literature of the Nath Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. T=\r\nhese are centers of psychological functions. 6 inside the human body and 3 =\r\ntoo subtle, or non-developed in most people, even seekers. It is my belief =\r\nthat each of the 9 Avataras - excluding Buddha - correspond to the full\n po=\r\nwer and force of one of these 9 Chakras. Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that w=\r\nhich can modify consciousness or allow the consciousness to explore and exp=\r\nress itself is various possiblities, are 9 in number. The lagna is a refere=\r\nnce point and not a graha. Therefore the chief Avatars who represent the pa=\r\nrable of evolution are nine in number. And the ninth of the sequence is yet=\r\n to come. 8. I cannot comment on which graha would typically represent whic=\r\nh Avatara. I know of what the BPHS says, however, it is my belief - feel fr=\r\nee to disagree with it -:)[one cannot rule out some deep-rooted corruption =\r\nof understanding or textual misrepresentation in this Kali-Yuga] - that the=\r\n Atmah among the Avataras has not yet appeared. It will be Kalki, or as Vim=\r\nalananda seems to say in the Aghora books, Nishkalanka - the stainless one.=\r\n There is only one thing which is perfectly stainless, the Atmah .After a N=\r\nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes living in the full and complete\n purity and m=\r\night and force and strength of the Atmah. By the sheer dint of his purity t=\r\nhe last Avatara will burn away opposing forces of this world and fulfill th=\r\ne purpose of evolution. Even Krshna used diplomacy at various points in his=\r\n adult life to achieve his ends. Kalki, I am speculating, won&#39;t even need t=\r\nhat. The white horse and that sword is a metaphor. He will be the only one =\r\ncapable enough to rectify the various errors and corruptions that beset our=\r\n age. Well, this is how I look at the story of Avataras. It is perfectly ok=\r\n not to agree with my views, but I am reasonably sanguine now that this is =\r\nwhat is closer to truth. -Regards =A0Rajarshi\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;awaktam wyaktimApa=\r\nnnam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:=\r\n24]\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;From: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;To: Vedic W=\r\nisdom &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt;&gt;&gt;Sent: Thursday, 25 April 2013 9:00=\r\n AM\n&gt;&gt;&gt;Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;=A0 \n&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;Namaste friends, =A0 There was a discussion on Lord Vishnu&#39;s Dasavataras =\r\non a limited access forum on Facebook. A learned friend wrote that &quot;Krshna =\r\nis the God-man&quot;, &quot;Previous Avatars are a build-up to this stage&quot; and &quot;Buddh=\r\na after Krshna is like going back from the linear progression of spirituali=\r\nty that the Avatars manifest one after the other upto Krshna&quot;. =A0 I want t=\r\no emphatically disagree with this notion that Dasavatars of a &quot;linear progr=\r\nession of spirituality..upto Krshna&quot;. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=\r\n=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Each avatara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfec=\r\nted form. =A0 Maharshi Parasara equated dasavataras with planets. For examp=\r\nle, Rama, Krishna and Narasimha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively. =A0 W=\r\ne also know that Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and=\r\n Ketu are personifications of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive, learning=\r\n spirit, wisdom/discrimination, spirit of enjoyment/being happy, patience/d=\r\niscipline,\n spirit of innovation/breaking barriers and detachment (respecti=\r\nvely). =A0 Correspondingly, each avatara is an expression of that aspect of=\r\n Supreme in a perfected form. Each story is an example of how that aspect o=\r\nperates. =A0 Lord Rama&#39;s story is a perfected example of how soul operates.=\r\n Lord Krishna&#39;s story is a perfected example of how mind operates. Lord Vam=\r\nana&#39;s story is a perfected example of how wisdom/discrimination operates. L=\r\nord Narasimha&#39;s story is a perfected example of how energy/drive/initiative=\r\n operates. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Now, let=\r\n us remember one basic thing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in us, learnin=\r\ng spirit in us, wisdom in us, happiness in us, discipline/patience in us - =\r\nall these are different manifestations of the same Self. However, when Self=\r\n manifests as these different aspects, it has different qualities and plays=\r\n different roles. There is no comparison between them. =A0 We MAY focus on =\r\none aspect of us first,\n perfect it and then perfect other aspects through =\r\nit. But, we need balance between all aspects in the end. Similarly, these d=\r\nifferent aspects of Supreme Being are incomparable and are in a balance wor=\r\nking together in the Cosmos. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=\r\n=A0 * =A0 One who is fascinated by the qualities of soul may like the story=\r\n that demonstrates how soul operates; one who is fascinated by the qualitie=\r\ns of mind may like the story that demonstrates how mind operates, and one w=\r\nho is fascinated by the qualities of wisdom may like the story that demonst=\r\nrates how wisdom operates. And so on. But this is just a matter of taste an=\r\nd subjective preference. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 =\r\n* =A0 Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen as=\r\n a representative of god in us, because of some basic attributes of it. It =\r\nis the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes. =A0 Once mind =\r\nfancies a separate existence with some\n agendas/desires, soul supports the =\r\nindividualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and sees it as its dh=\r\narma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of this individualized =\r\nconsciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning ability, enjoyment, d=\r\niscipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no desires/agendas/likes=\r\n/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and records all of one&#39;s =\r\nagendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper fruits later on. It d=\r\noes all that despite full awareness that it is neither doing those karmas n=\r\nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the individualized co=\r\nnsciousness entertain the notion that they are doing things and begetting t=\r\nhe fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It sees that as its dharm=\r\na and does it impassionately. =A0 Now, does this sound exciting? Perhaps no=\r\nt to all. This functionality of an impassionate witness supporting the play=\r\n, may not seem interesting enough\n to some. =A0 On the other hand, mind has=\r\n likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly pursuing those agendas, gett=\r\ning things and achieving things. Movement of mind is what keeps the individ=\r\nualization going!!! Though soul is the support for everything else in the i=\r\nndividualized consciousness, soul is a witness doing its dharma impassionat=\r\nely. It is mind that keeps the individualization going and brings in agenda=\r\ns and passion and even decides/affects every entity&#39;s dharma. That way, min=\r\nd is really the &quot;boss&quot; of the individualization. No wonder Krishna&#39;s life a=\r\nppeals more to one who may be excited by this description! =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=\r\n=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Lord Krishna is obviously awe-ins=\r\npiring, but let me put Rama&#39;s life in perspective. =A0 Rama&#39;s life demonstr=\r\nates how soul operates. At a young age, he received Brahma Jnana from Vasis=\r\nhtha and became realized. Yet, he did whatever was his &quot;dharma&quot;. He helped =\r\nVishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was given\n kingdom. At the last moment=\r\n, his father banished him to forest at the behest of his step-mother and hi=\r\ns step-brother was given the throne. He had no complaints. Though his fathe=\r\nr, step-mother and step-brother felt guilty to various degrees, he himself =\r\nsupported and consoled all three and followed his dharma impassionately. Th=\r\nough he knew leaving Sita in the forest with Lakshmana and going after the =\r\ngolden deer would cause problems, he did it impassionately when Sita insist=\r\ned. When she was kidnapped by Ravana, he searched for her and fought the ba=\r\nttle. He never faulted Sita for forcing him to leave her or faulted Lakshma=\r\nna for leaving her later. He accepted every life situation with no complain=\r\nts and did the best possible action then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did =\r\nso without hatred or anger, but as his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana =\r\nwas dying, he went to him and respectfully learned some subjects that were =\r\ngoing to disappear with Ravana! =A0 Rama\n is a perfect example of a liberat=\r\ned man with no desires or agendas who impassionately discharges one&#39;s dharm=\r\na arising from the momentum of karmas before liberation. THAT is basically =\r\nwhat soul does! =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 As =\r\nanother example, let us look at Lord Vaamana. His story is a perfect demons=\r\ntration of how wisdom/discrimination operates. =A0 He was born as a learned=\r\n pygmy. He filled the entire cosmos to rid earth of a charitable demon king=\r\n with many great qualities. =A0 Wisdom/discrimination makes one humble and =\r\nunassuming. When one is doing good work but tainted with demonic qualities =\r\n(e.g. pride or attachment), one&#39;s discrimination is not pleased until that =\r\npride is suppressed. When wisdom fills one&#39;s entire consciousness, then dem=\r\nonic qualities are completely suppressed. =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=\r\n=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 Please think about the other avataras. The stories=\r\n can be understood as perfect demonstrations of how various aspects of\n our=\r\n consciousness operate, based on clues from Maharshi Parasara. =A0 Let us n=\r\not compare Dasavataras, but celebrate each of them separately. Of course, i=\r\nf you are more attracted to one of them, please think about that avatara mo=\r\nre and develop devotion. They are ALL capable of relieving us from samsara.=\r\n =A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 *=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 * =A0 By the way, happy =\r\nHanumajjayanti to those who celebrate it today (there are different schools=\r\n of thought). =A0 Best regards, Narasimha -------- Astrology & Spirituality=\r\n Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org -------- \n&gt;\r\n--61789334-444787131-1367930557=:4558\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=iso-8859-1\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color:#000; background-color:#fff; font-family:ar=\r\nial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size:10pt&quot;&gt;&lt;div id=3D&quot;yiv2035484844&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;=\r\ndiv style=3D&quot;color:#000;background-color:#fff;font-family:arial, helvetica,=\r\n sans-serif;font-size:10pt;&quot;&gt;Dear Rajarshi,&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;&lt;&lt;I believe =\r\nin the evolutionary parable of these 9 Avatara because I find no other reas=\r\non why these set of Avatara, from the whole list of possible Avataras, have=\r\n captured the popular imagination.&gt;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;If capturing the po=\r\npular imagination is the criterion, then Narasimha, Rama and Krishna are th=\r\ne most popular ones among the 9. Why are the *4th*, 7th and 8th avataras mo=\r\nst popular if there is a nice &quot;evolutionary&quot; sequence among the 9???&lt;br&gt;&nb=\r\nsp;&lt;br&gt;There is a very simple explanation, if one throws away the notion of=\r\n &quot;evolutionary&quot; sequence. These are *poornavataras*, completely divine and =\r\ndevoid of jeevatmamsa, as per Parasara. In contrast, the 5th and 6th\n avata=\r\nras did have some jeevatmamsa in them.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbs=\r\np;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp=\r\n;&lt;br&gt;&lt;&lt;I mean Dattatreya is an Avatara too as per SB. His spiritualit=\r\ny is no less than that of any other Avatara. Yet, he is not in the list of =\r\n9/10 Avataras.&gt;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;First of all, dasavataras are not a &quot;to=\r\np 10&quot; short-list of SB&#39;s list. SB list gives the avataras of Supreme Being =\r\n(&quot;Purusha&quot; as it calls). Dasavataras OTOH are specifically of Vishnu, who i=\r\ns the &quot;sustaining principle&quot; of Purusha. Dattatreya is an avatara of Brahma=\r\n, Vishnu and Shiva together, i.e. creative, sustaining and destructive prin=\r\nciples of Purusha combined together. That is why he is not among Dasavatara=\r\ns. That does not make him any less or more. His purpose/functionality is si=\r\nmply different from that of Rama, Krishna, Narasimha, or Venkateswara. Just=\r\n in terms of &quot;popularity&quot;, he is actually more popular than\n some of the da=\r\nsavataras.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Secondly, rather than *comparing* avataras in terms=\r\n like &quot;less&quot; or more in &quot;spirituality&quot;, try to *understand* avataras from t=\r\nhe point of view of what functionality and role they play in the functionin=\r\ng of collective cosmic consciousness. THAT is the key to understanding them=\r\n and their place in cosmos. And also to internalizing them eventually..&lt;br&gt;=\r\n&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;*&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&n=\r\nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; *&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Whether you call the Supreme Being as=\r\n Purusha or Krishna or Shiva or Surya or Narayana does not really matter, f=\r\nor Scriptures are clear that He is beyond names or descriptions.&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;If your devotion to Him is steadfast, if your notion of Him expands with=\r\n time beyond the initial notions you start off with, and if the paramatmams=\r\na in you is able to resonate to Him and the conditioning of your jeevatmams=\r\na is being overcome, that is all that\n matters!&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br&gt;Best regards,&lt;=\r\nbr&gt;Narasimha&lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;Astrology &amp; Spirituality Resources: http://=\r\nwww.VedicAstrologer.org&lt;br&gt;--------&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;br id=3D&quot;yiv2035484844yu=\r\ni_3_7_2_32_1367853193997_63&quot;&gt;&lt;blockquote id=3D&quot;yiv2035484844yui_3_7_2_32_13=\r\n67853193997_66&quot; style=3D&quot;border-left:2px solid rgb(16, 16, 255);margin-left=\r\n:5px;margin-top:5px;padding-left:5px;&quot;&gt;  &lt;div class=3D&quot;yiv2035484844yui_3_7=\r\n_2_32_1367853193997_70&quot; style=3D&quot;font-family:arial, helvetica, sans-serif;f=\r\nont-size:10pt;&quot;&gt; &lt;div class=3D&quot;yiv2035484844yui_3_7_2_32_1367853193997_71&quot; =\r\nstyle=3D&quot;font-family:times new roman, new york, times, serif;font-size:12pt=\r\n;&quot;&gt; &lt;div dir=3D&quot;ltr&quot;&gt; &lt;hr size=3D&quot;1&quot;&gt;  &lt;font face=3D&quot;Arial&quot; size=3D&quot;2&quot;&gt; &lt;b&gt;=\r\n&lt;span style=3D&quot;font-weight:bold;&quot;&gt;From:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt; rajarshi nandy &lt;rajar=\r\nshi14@...&gt;&lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=3D&quot;font-weight:bold;&quot;&gt;To:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/=\r\nb&gt; &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; &lt;br&gt;=\r\n &lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=3D&quot;font-weight:bold;&quot;&gt;Sent:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt;\n Monday, May 6, 2013=\r\n 8:07 AM&lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt;&lt;span style=3D&quot;font-weight:bold;&quot;&gt;Subject:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/b&gt; Re: [=\r\nvedic-wisdom] Re: Comparing Dasavataras!&lt;br&gt; 